@node About
================================
 About PalmSync
================================

This project is my first attempt at writing something in Gui4Cli,
so it is naturally simple. But then, simplicity is often something
that gets overlooked in software development. If you're expecting
a flashy GUI interface, then this isn't the software you're
looking for.

I own a Palm Pilot Pro and use the PalmLink and PalmTransfer
software to sync data between Amiga and Palm. Although there are
graphical hotsync apps for the Amiga, I prefer a very basic shell
tool to do the work - nothing fancy. However, the lack of GUI can
often be a pain, and the shell aliases are fine for most use but
not always flexible enough.

Anyway, Dimitris Keletsekis contacted me by e-mail and introduced
me to the concept of Gui4Cli. After 30 mins of playing about, the
very first version of this interface had been completed. ToolTypes
support was added during a spare moment several days later to form
the first release. It's rough, and simple, but usable - I use it
constantly for backups, installations and restores on my own Palm
Pilot Pro, and a development Palm III on loan from work.

I've not released any software for the Amiga publicly before, but
felt this should be shared with the community at large. Expect
more elaborate projects from me in the future - many with a
Palm/Amiga integration feel, since that's primarily where I'm find
gaps in the Amiga software market ;-)

@endnode
@node Requirements
===============================
 Requirements
===============================

PalmLink by Richard Koerber
Gui4Cli  by Dimitris Keletsekis

...and an Amiga and Palm device.

If you haven't got these already then I'm not sure why you
downloaded this ;-)


Gui4Cli is available from The Gui4Cli WWW Page:
 http://users.hol.gr/~dck/gcmain.htm

PalmLink is available from Aminet:
 /util/lib/PalmLink.lha


@endnode
@node Installation
===============================
 Installation
===============================

Copy PalmSync.gc and its icon to a location of your choice.

It's as simple as that, assuming you have Gui4Cli and PalmLink
already installed. Ensure PalmTransfer is in your path (I keep
mine in C:)

@endnode
